<div id="review_2182353803" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2182353803" />
    <a title="Bobbieshiann" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/39394999-bobbieshiann"><img alt="Bobbieshiann" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1496365582p2/39394999.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2182353803?book_show_action=true">Jul 05, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bobbieshiann" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bobbieshiann" href="/user/show/39394999-bobbieshiann">Bobbieshiann</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/39394999-bobbieshiann?shelf=one-time-was-not-enough">one-time-was-not-enough</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/39394999-bobbieshiann?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2182353803" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17819899032172408456">In the spring of 1940, “The murder had white man written all over it. But no one would say it above a whisper. It was 1940. It was Bigelow, Arkansas. It was a black child. Need anymore be said”? <br/><br/>Sugar is a story that shows how two women cross paths at harsh times in their lives, and how like a magnet, nothing could disconnect them for long. In the spring of 1955, the typical Black woman in this time is everything that Sugar is not. A Black woman is a mother with no less than 4 kids who works all</span>
  <span id="freeText17819899032172408456" style="display:none">In the spring of 1940, “The murder had white man written all over it. But no one would say it above a whisper. It was 1940. It was Bigelow, Arkansas. It was a black child. Need anymore be said”? <br /><br />Sugar is a story that shows how two women cross paths at harsh times in their lives, and how like a magnet, nothing could disconnect them for long. In the spring of 1955, the typical Black woman in this time is everything that Sugar is not. A Black woman is a mother with no less than 4 kids who works all day then tends to her husband and children with no break in between. She is a woman who does it all but can because, “her body can function off 3 hours of sleep”. Sugar Lacey was raised in a brothel with nature as her close companion. Not understanding what a mamma is but knowing what it’s like to lay there and let men use her body.<br /><br />Pearl is a woman who loss her only daughter. She has never fully healed and while she is still broken, Sugar struts into town and moves right across the street. As you learn of Sugars past, lonlieness screams at you from the pages. She was unwanted from birth only to be wanted for her body. <br /><br />“Sugar was ashamed to share her ordeal with them. Stories filled with abusive men, broken limbs and nights when her belly burned empty with hunger, her soul with loneliness”. <br /><br />The entwining of Pearl and Sugar’s relationship is a magical connection. It was not built off of happiness and truth. It was built off misunderstanding, loneliness, loss, and a pull that automatically connected both women together. (Of course they had their share of road bumps, but like a magnet, they came back to each other). <br /><br />Bernice did me in with this story! My introduction of her writing is simply amazing <br />#theyearofbernicemcfaddden<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="17819899032172408456" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


