<div id="review_1303429619" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1303429619" />
    <a title="Tangee" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/43818991-tangee"><img alt="Tangee" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1515968957p2/43818991.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1303429619?book_show_action=true">Jun 09, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tangee" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tangee" href="/user/show/43818991-tangee">Tangee</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1303429619" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15577949533485277102">I finished reading this book today and I know that its a book that will be a &quot;go-to&quot; book that I will re-read in my collection. I was drawn in from the character development in this book. The way that you see the growth spiritually and mentally from the two main characters in this book is really touching. I found myself connected to Sugar and Pearl (2 main characters) within the first couple chapters. The way that Bernice McFadden writes is nothing less than spectacular; I was drawn to the diale</span>
  <span id="freeText15577949533485277102" style="display:none">I finished reading this book today and I know that its a book that will be a "go-to" book that I will re-read in my collection. I was drawn in from the character development in this book. The way that you see the growth spiritually and mentally from the two main characters in this book is really touching. I found myself connected to Sugar and Pearl (2 main characters) within the first couple chapters. The way that Bernice McFadden writes is nothing less than spectacular; I was drawn to the dialect of the characters, the way all the characters interacted and the way Bernice molded the story to connect. I recommend this book to anyone looking for something in correlation to Zora Neale Hurston. The old family secrets, the growth of the characters, the emotions that this book gave me were fantastic. I love the ending because it was not fabricated or a typical "ending"- it was realistic and I loved it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15577949533485277102" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


